:[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECerebral perfusion pressure (CPP) is a critical physiological parameter that represents the pressure gradient driving cerebral blood flow. \u003Cstrong\u003EMean arterial pressure minus intracranial pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct formula for calculating CPP. This relationship explains why both hypotension and raised intracranial pressure can compromise cerebral blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMean arterial pressure plus intracranial pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as this would give falsely elevated values and does not represent the actual pressure gradient driving cerebral blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracranial pressure minus mean arterial pressure\u003C/strong\u003E would give a negative value and is the inverse of the correct formula.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystolic blood pressure minus intracranial pressure\u003C/strong\u003E would overestimate CPP as it does not account for diastolic pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiastolic blood pressure minus intracranial pressure\u003C/strong\u003E would underestimate CPP as it does not account for systolic pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENormal CPP should be maintained between 60-70 mmHg to ensure adequate cerebral blood flow. Values below this threshold can lead to cerebral ischaemia, while excessive CPP may contribute to cerebral oedema. Management strategies focus on controlling both MAP and ICP to maintain adequate CPP.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cerebral perfusion pressure (CPP) is calculated as mean arterial pressure (MAP) minus intracranial pressure (ICP).","Normal cerebral perfusion pressure should be maintained above 60 mmHg to prevent cerebral ischaemia.","Increased intracranial pressure reduces cerebral perfusion pressure and can lead to secondary brain injury."],"references":["G\u00fciza F, 